summary:
Iran launched missile attacks on the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, and Saudi Arabia. Missiles prompted sirens in Dubai and Bahrain, while Saudi Arabia downed two drones. Five pro-Iran militants died in an Iraq airstrike. This follows Israel's strikes on Tehran oil depots yesterday. Gulf states report heightened risks, with more retaliation expected. The attacks escalate the regional war affecting global oil security.

US President Trump warned of massive strikes if Iran blocks the Strait of Hormuz, after Revolutionary Guards threatened to halt oil exports. Brent crude prices reached $101.19 per barrel yesterday amid the conflict. G7 finance ministers agreed to measures stabilizing oil prices over $100, including discussions on energy supply support and possible reserve releases. Kentucky Army Sgt. Benjamin Pennington, 26, died from wounds in a March 1 attack on a Saudi base, marking the seventh US casualty. The war drives up global energy and fertilizer prices, raising costs in nations like Pakistan and complicating inflation controls.

Israel allowed displaced Palestinians to stream back into northern Gaza after a hostage release deal. Rwanda-backed rebels overran Congolese troops and entered Goma, with gunfire and shelling displacing over one million into the aid hub. Human Rights Watch verified images of airburst munitions, identified as white phosphorus, over Yohmor in Lebanon on March 3, causing fires; Israel may investigate. NASA and SpaceX launched Crew-10 with astronauts McClain, Ayers, Onishi, and Peskov from Florida on Friday to retrieve Wilmore and Williams after nine months on the ISS. NATO mounted a coordinated response after another Baltic Sea deep-sea cable severance, increasing patrols on energy and data links."}
